Day 1 - Learned how to query active network connections by using the command: ifconfig. Basic knowledge about 
network interfaace card (NIC), media access control (MAC) (Hwaddr), and internet protocol (IP). For IP, researched about Bcast or
broadcast address which sends information to all IP address on the subnet (haven't learned it yet). Netmask or network mask, 
which determines what part of the IP add is connected to the local network. Show Network Statistics with netstat (old way to show network statistics)
or use ss command for the modern and more readable format. Can use options like (-u -t -l -a). Use -u for UDP connections which means
User Datagram Protocol, -t for Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) connections, -l for listening connections, -a for showing all sockets. 
Used the command: iwconfig, to check wireless network devices. Assigned or SPOOF a new IP Address using sudo ifconfig <network> <newip>
for MAC Address, sudo ifconfig eth0 down, sudo ifconfig eth0 hw ether <add>, sudo ifconfig eth0 up. Assigning new IP address from DHCP server using
sudo dhclient eth0 (had problems running this command). Manipulate DNS using dig <dns-server> <type> which I learned to use mx - mailserver, ns - nameserver
change DNS server using the command mousepad. sudo mousepad /etc/resolv.conf, can do overwriting with echo command. Mapping your own IP addr
with mousepad again using: sudo mousepad /etc/hosts. -EOD 

Day 2 - Review about Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) which is used to download and install, update, amd upgrade new software packages with it. Using the
sudo apt search <keyword>, you can check whether a package is available. To search for uncomplicated firewall (ufw), which is a powerful Linux firewall to protect
your network, use the command: sudo apt search ufw. To install a software in your OS's defaulr repo in the terminal, use sudo apt install <packagename>. Then enter 
the word Y to proceed install. When we want to remove a software simply use sudo apt remove <packagename>. Once again enter Y to confirm uninstallation. The remove
command doesn't remove the configuration files, which means you can reinstall the same package and it will have the same configuration as before. If you want to remove 
the package with the configuration files use the command sudo apt purge <package>. Enter Y to continue purging the software package with the configuration. Software repositories
will periodically update with new software or versions and it will not automatically update. Updating is different from Upgrading, updating means simply to UPDATE the list of packages
available for download from the repo meanwhile upgrading UPGRADES the package to the latest version in the repo. Use the command sudo apt update to update your individual system to search
for available updates available. To upgrade existing packages on your system enter the command: sudo apt upgrade. This will upgrade every package on your system APT knows about,
which means only those stored in the repository. - Finished @page 43

Day 3 - null 

Day 4 - Continued the Adding and Removing Software lesson, repositories is the servers that hold the software for a particular destribution of linux. Whick kali linux has 
a large amoynt of security and hacking software. If you want to add a backup repository that your system can search through in case it doesn't find it a specific software in the Kali repository.
The repos your system will search for software are stored in the sources.list file, with this you can alter this file and define which repos you want to download software. The sources.list file 
is located at /etc/apt/sources.list and open it with any text editor in which we can use themousepad text editor. Again we'll be using the command sudo mousepad /etc/apt/sources.list. Newer Kali versions 
no longer include GUI-based software installation. We can install one using the apt command, two of the most popular gui based installation tools are Synaptic and Gdebi. I'll be using the Synaptic tool. 
Use the command sudo apt install synaptic. Once installed, you can start it in the Kali menu by going to Settings > Synaptic Package Manager. Sometimes the software you want isn't available, so maybe you can find it on github. 
For example, you want to install a tool but it isn't in the Kali repository, you can use githhub to install it. If you found your tool at github, you can clone it to your system with the command git clone <githuburl>. 
then enter ls -l to check of you've successfully downloaded the tool. 

